english:
  title: 'A Libation for Hwangbo Won: Spoken in My Father''s Stead'
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A brilliant spirit is heaven's private gift, yet those who hunger without satiation invite ruin by necessity's hand. Righteousness is despised by shadowed ghosts, and those who walk it boldly must bear contempt. Rare renown stirs the envy of common men, and those who grasp it too early shall see it shattered. You possessed all three—who would deny that your fall was of your own making?

    Had you been dull and incapable, how could misfortune have found you so early? But no—you carried the will to save the world, yet your virtue could not reach the people. You held talents of surpassing worth, only to perish in exile. Wrapped in loyalty and bound by faith, the poison settled in your very marrow. I thought of your luminous gifts, destined to honor your house, yet instead came your ruin, now weighing upon your family's name.

    False rumors struck at the righteous man; those who investigated found no truth, yet judgment fell. The boundless sea was given to cross, the towering mountains to traverse—can we doubt the sickness that followed? Inner grief kindled the fire; corruption crept across your skin. Distant from your brothers, seeking physicians and shamans, in a single night you passed into death. The heavens know nothing, yet dared commit this slaughter. I would have cried your injustice before the throne itself, but before my heart could act, I too was torn away to a strange realm.

    When I first heard of your passing, my breath stopped, then returned. Dreams blur with waking—what is real? The Creator's work shows no justice in its distribution. Fortune flows to the corrupt; calamity strikes the upright. Your fate proved this: exile and death, your righteousness unredeemed. I lack words enough to voice this sorrow; all the mouths beneath heaven cannot cry out your wrong.

    The vile grow rich and live long—does virtue matter? The deceitful prosper; the stubborn endure. Such things bring you shame, yet I cannot offer condolences—only shame upon myself for falling short of wisdom. My affection pours forth for you, my friend. Here is wine in my cup; I pour it out in your honor.
  footnotes:
    - This is a ritual sacrificial text (祭文) composed by Lim Chun to honor Hwangbo Won (a historical figure who was persecuted and exiled), delivered on behalf of Lim Chun's father. The genre allowed for philosophical reflection on injustice and fate.
    - 'The text reflects Neo-Confucian concerns about moral paradoxes: how virtue can lead to destruction while vice is rewarded. This was a common literary preoccupation during Korea''s Goryeo period.'
    - The final gesture of pouring wine is a traditional libation offering that transforms the lament into an act of reverence and remembrance.
